        public PropertyChangeEvent(IEventSource eventSource,
                           java.lang.String eventType,
                           java.lang.Object object,
                           java.lang.Object property,
                           java.lang.Object oldValue,
                           java.lang.Object newValue,
                           int position,
                           java.lang.Object data)
        Creates a new delta event with the given event source, modified object, event type, modified property, old property value, new property value and a list position.
        Parameters:
        eventSource - The event source; must not be null
        eventType - The event type; must not be null and must be one of:
        1. IPropertyChangeEvent.SET
        2. IPropertyChangeEvent.UNSET
        3. IPropertyChangeEvent.ADD
        4. IPropertyChangeEvent.REMOVE
        5. IPropertyChangeEvent.ADD_MANY
        6. IPropertyChangeEvent.REMOVE_MANY
        7. IPropertyChangeEvent.MOVE
        object - The modified object; must not be null
        property - The modified property; must not be null
        oldValue - The old value of the modified property; may be null
        newValue - The new value of the modified property; may be null
        position - The position
        data - The extra data that is attached to the event. Particular event sources that fire property change events should document what the extra data is.
        See Also:
        Event.getEventSource(), getObject(), Event.getEventType(), getProperty(), getOldValue(), getNewValue(), getPosition(), #geteData()

        public final java.lang.Object getOldValue()
        Description copied from interface: IPropertyChangeEvent
        Returns the value of the object's property before the change occurred. For a list-based property, this represents a value, or a list of values, removed from the list. For a move, this represents the old position of the moved value.
        Specified by:

      • addCategories

        protected void addCategories(java.util.List categories)
        Description copied from class: Event
        Adds additional categories for this event to the given list. Note that the event's event type will be included automatically, so there is no need to add it. Categories must be distinct non-null objects that can be compared with equals.

        The Event implementation of this method does nothing. Subclasses should extend this method if they have additional categories. Extended methods must call super.addCategories(categories) to include categories contributed by superclasses.

        Overrides:
        addCategories in class Event
        Parameters:
        categories - the list of categories (element type: Object); never null
